A trick I do is I try to remind myself what I’m hoping for by having that drink versus what I actually get. E.g., I want that gin and tonic to unwind, relax on the patio while I read… but what I get is five drinks later trying to hide the fact that I’m pretty drunk from my husband, making mistakes while I make dinner, feeling super shitty and depressed the next morning… I know I’ll get cravings this weekend (because the weekend is when all my “cues” come up), so I’m going to try to change up my routine, keep busy by doing a lot of cleaning, have some NA beers/ iced coffees. Just remember that you won’t regret getting through today without drinking, but if you have that drink you’re back to square one only to face the cravings of day nine again in the future.

Often by doing this I get one of two reactions, people who are genuinely interested and often talk about their own drinking, or those who cannot believe anyone could ever give up alcohol, this says more about them than you! Consider alcohol free options – One of the best things about not drinking alcohol, is the choice of drinks these days is endless. Alcohol free beer and wine has got much better in recent years, a personal favourite of mine is Lucky Saint beer. Or if alcohol free is not for you, have something different with your Christmas dinner, have a milkshake, a cup of tea or try Kombucha, your choices are endless. Treat yourself – Christmas is a time for indulgence and think of all those calories that you will be saving by not drinking.

In the first few months after I quit booze, I drank a lot of NA beer and wine because I craved the taste of alcohol. After about 4-5 months, though, the cravings went away. I now have a NA beer once every few weeks or so. For me, it never provoked a relapse, but obviously everyone reacts differently. (Disclaimer: Beer has never been a huge source of temptation for me. I was a wine and spirits drinker. The NA wine available in my area is so terrible that I gave up on it, and NA spirits are too expensive to justify. If I had *good* NA wine or spirits, that could have been a slippery slope. NA beer isn't going to do that *for me*.)
